==English==

===Etymology===
Equivalent to {{suffix|en|tight|en|id2=inchoative}}. From {{inh|en|enm|tighten}}, from {{inh|en|ang|tyhtan}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/ˈtaɪ.tən/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/ˈtaɪ.tən/|[ˈtʰaɪ̯.ʔn̩]}}
** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-tighten.wav|Audio (UK)}}
* {{rhymes|en|aɪtən|s=2}}
* {{homophones|en|titan|Titan}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To make [[tight]]er.
#: {{ux|en|Please '''tighten''' that screw a quarter-turn.}}
#* '''1760''', {{w|Francis Fawkes}}, ''Works of Anacreon, Sappho, Bion, Moschus, and Musæus translated into English by a gentleman of Cambridge''
#*: Just where I please, with '''tighten;d''' rein / I'll urge thee round the dusty plain.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To become tighter.
#: {{ux|en|That joint is '''tightening''' as the wood dries.}}
# {{lb|en|economics}} To make money harder to borrow or obtain.
#: {{ux|en|If the government doesn't '''tighten''' the money supply, inflation is certain to be harsh.}}
# {{lb|en|economics}} To raise short-term interest rates.
#: {{ux|en|The Fed is expected to '''tighten''' by a quarter-point.}}

